  "prompt": "What is the best code troll you've ever seen?",
  "response": "One classic code troll is the infamous \"goto\" statement. It's often used as a joke in programming communities to highlight poor coding practices. For example, you might find a function that looks something like this:\n\n```python\ndef do_something():\n    goto end\n\n    # Imagine there's supposed to be some real logic here\n    print(\"This code is never reached!\")\n\nend:\n    return\n```\n\nThis intentionally humorous misuse of `goto` mocks the idea of jumping around code unpredictably, something that most modern programming practices frown upon. It's a playful reminder of why structured programming is generally preferred, and it can elicit a good laugh from developers who know better.\n\nAnother common troll involves using comments in a way that misleads or confuses, such as:\n\n```python\n# This function does something really complicated\ndef do_nothing():\n    pass  # Do nothing, literally\n```\n\nBoth examples illustrate how humor can be found in coding practices, often playing on the frustrations or misconceptions that developers encounter.",
